The Familiarity with the New Antisemitism
Why do so many Holocaust survivors sense emerging threats to Judaism even before they become visibly apparent?
Because they know that the supposedly "harmless" hints will turn into accusations and eventually lead to discrimination, which is then enshrined in law.
At this point, hysteria sets in.
The survivors sound the alarm because they know what is at stake in the game.
With this, they strengthen our democracies in a way that only they can.
The sentence translates to: "We listen to the survivors so that we may also survive."
Since the first round of the French presidential elections, it is clear that we have every reason to listen.
But problems are not caused by demagogues like Jean Marie Le Pen or other boorish right-wing extremists in Europe alone.
In the 20th century, people who saw themselves as "intellectuals" were often stepping stones for fascism or communism, without joining a party with the corresponding ideological background.
In the 21st century, we deal with people - with the "educational bourgeoisie" in connection with mass media, politics, government, and universities - who condemn Israel in a language that often resembles that of the perpetrators of these anti-democratic movements.
This is not about the majority opinion in the Western world - not yet, fortunately - but it is the voices of a powerful and influential minority.
At this point, the example of the French ambassador to the United Kingdom should be mentioned: Not long ago, he referred to Israel during a dinner party in London as "this damn little country."
His vulgar language is not particularly alarming.
More disturbing are the reactions to it.
Neither was he recalled by his government, nor did the government demand Blair's recall. The matter was brushed aside as merely a scandal in public.
The French press portrayed the ambassador as an actual victim of British tabloids and not of his own despicable conduct.
Unfortunately, the French ambassador to Britain has several allies among Europe's elites.
Ambassador Bernard, however, rendered us a service: through him, it became clear how widespread these new anti-Jewish resentments are.
As a columnist so aptly put it: Israel has become an object of hate whose very name one dares not utter.
But we must not only dare to speak it, we are even obligated to express it.
Given the daily attacks against Jews and synagogues in France, we must not remain silent.
It is a shame for all of Europe that so many French Jews cannot send their children to school without having to worry about their safety.
Anti-Semitic attacks are also reported in other places, such as Berlin and London, in Switzerland, Italy, Sweden, the Netherlands, and in parts of Eastern Europe.
We must not remain silent about the fact that denial of the Holocaust is becoming commonplace. Similarly, we must not remain silent about the comparisons that antisemites and anti-Zionists draw between Israel and the Third Reich.
While Palestinian television depicts Israeli soldiers as rapists and cold-blooded murderers, a Syrian newspaper wrote that we must "meet the new Nazi plague that is emerging in Israel."
The Mufti of Jerusalem said: "It is not my fault that Hitler hated the Jews. They are almost hated everywhere."
During the live television broadcast of a Friday prayer on Palestinian television, the preacher urged Muslims to "show no mercy to the Jews. No matter where you are, kill them and these Americans who are just like them."
What we should think about in connection with antisemitism is that it always begins with the Jews but never ends with the Jews.
If anti-Semitism is not contained, it almost always leads to attacks on other groups and minorities and ultimately undermines democratic institutions and the rule of law.
The fight against antisemitism is therefore the task of Jews as well as non-Jews.
The current attack vectors in this struggle are blurrier than ever before, as a surprising aspect of contemporary antisemitism is its flexibility.
Although the aim of antisemitism remains the same – namely, to attack Jews – it nevertheless changes its appearance, its strategy, its rationalizations, and even its vocabulary.
Once, the Jewish religion was the target.
When this was not given up, the Jews were driven out or killed.
When racial theory captivated people in the 19th century, Jews were attacked because of their membership in a supposedly evil race.
With the existence of the state of Israel as a source of pride and protection for most Jews, Zionism is today disparaged as a racist ideology.
I do not equate criticism of Israel with antisemitism.
Just as with other nations, it is completely legitimate to critically stand opposed to certain political strategies and decisions made by Israel.
The anti-Zionism is, however, becoming increasingly similar to antisemitism.
Anti-Zionists sometimes claim that they are not against Jews themselves, but "only" against the Jewish state.
Imagine someone saying: "I am only against the existence of Great Britain, but I am not anti-British!"
Or if someone claimed: "I love the Swedish people, but Sweden should be abolished."
They would not believe them.
It is difficult to love or respect a people but to hate their state.
And yet, there are people in connection with Israel who pretend to be able to do exactly that.
In various UN organizations, criticizing Israel is on the agenda.
The demonization of the only democratic state institution in the Middle East is a key aspect of this new antisemitism.
When Israel is described as "the enemy of all that is good and the source of all evil," then, as Professor Irwin Cotler, a member of the Canadian Parliament, expresses it, the "teachings of contempt" circulate within the UN.
Translating the given German sentence to English yields:  "This permanent portrayal of a nation as an enemy of humanity is in reality a campaign against the Jewish people."
The numerous anti-Jewish assaults in many countries are based on demonizations of Israel that rely on antisemitic terminology.
Attacks on synagogues are often triggered by the use of this slanderous language in relation to the Middle East.
Compared to earlier anti-Jewish outbursts, today's antisemitism is less about attacks on individual Jews and more about an attack on the "collective Jew," that is, against the State of Israel.
Such attacks sparked a chain reaction of assaults on individual Jews and Jewish institutions across Europe and Latin America.
The earliest dangerous antisemites were those who wanted to make the world Judenrein (lit. "Jew-free").
The most dangerous antisemites of today are those who want to make the world Judenrein.
